#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail
# The orchestrator. Discovers the software in libexec/, presents a checklist of the
# pieces this host can run, and drives install/uninstall/status across the whole set.
# The only thing it discovers and selects is software: the per-OS file
# libexec/<os>_<version>/software/<name>.sh, the OS token resolved here through
# lib/os.sh. The default interactive flow ticks the software to set up, then runs
# three phases: collect every piece's inputs, refresh the host package manager,
# install and configure each piece. After the software it runs the post-install
# provisioners (the workspace and the dotfiles): a fixed pair, not software but
# personal configuration the toolkit applies last, driven in-process through the
# framework (lib/provisioner.sh) rather than from any executable of their own. They
# are never discovered or listed beside the software; the interactive flow offers them
# their own toggle menu after the install, and provisions the ones left ticked. A
# provisioner gathers its one input when it runs (so the installer location is asked
# right before it runs) and fetches and runs the repository's installer script, last,
# on top of the freshly installed tools; that script downloads the repository and lays
# it down on its own. There is no ordering between software pieces; the provisioners
# run in a fixed order (the workspace before the dotfiles). A named, unattended run
# installs exactly the named software and never touches the provisioners. Removal is a
# separate action (uninstall) and covers software only: it stages the same way (collect
# inputs, then unconfigure and uninstall); the provisioners own no checkout and have
# nothing to remove.
#
# This file is the flow only: the software mechanics and menus live in lib/software.sh
# and the provisioner menu and run in lib/provisioner.sh.

# ─── Functions ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

#--------------------------------------------------
# Function:
#   machine_setup::usage
#
# Description:
#   Prints the usage reference to stdout.
#
# Arguments:
#   N/A
#
# Returns:
#   0 always
#
# Example:
#   machine_setup::usage
#--------------------------------------------------
machine_setup::usage() {
    cat <<'EOF'
Usage: machine-setup [install] [name...]
       machine-setup uninstall [name...]
       machine-setup status [name...]

Set up this machine: select the software, collect its inputs, then install or update
and configure it, then run the post-install provisioners. Removing software is a
separate, explicit action: uninstall.

With no names, install opens an interactive checklist of the software this host can
run (pre-ticked from a previous run, or every available piece on a first run) for you
to adjust; after the install it offers a second toggle menu for the workspace and
dotfiles provisioners (both ticked) and runs the ones you leave ticked. uninstall with
no names opens a checklist of the installed software, every entry unticked and labelled
with its current status, for you to pick what to remove. Given one or more names either
action skips the menus and acts on exactly that software, for an unattended run; a
named install never touches the provisioners. With no terminal the menus fall back to
their ticked sets (install to its pre-ticked software then both provisioners, uninstall
to nothing).

  machine-setup                 Choose software interactively, set it up, then provision.
  machine-setup tree git        Set up the named software unattended (no provisioners).
  machine-setup uninstall       Choose installed software to remove from a menu.
  machine-setup uninstall tree  Unconfigure and remove the named software.
  machine-setup status [name]   Report a status table of the software.

Software is the per-OS file libexec/<os>_<version>/software/<name>.sh, the host OS
resolved by the orchestrator. A piece reports 'unavailable' on a host it cannot run on
(for example a GUI app on a headless host) and is left out of the menu.

The workspace and dotfiles provisioners are not software and are never listed beside
it: they are a fixed post-install step of the interactive flow that fetches a
self-contained installer script and runs it, last, so the personal configuration
lands on top of the freshly installed tools; the script downloads its repository and
lays it down on its own. They own no executable and run only through this flow, never
a named run. A provisioner asks for its one input when it runs, not up front: where
the installer comes from (blank keeps the default), either an URL fetched to a
temporary file and run (with wget or curl) or a path to a local executable. The
earlier identity toolkit (SSH/GPG keygen, gitconfig wiring, the secret store) now
lives in those external repos.

Environment:
  MACHINE_SETUP_LIBEXEC_DIR  Directory holding the per-OS software executables (default: ../libexec).
  MACHINE_SETUP_SHARE_DIR    Directory holding share/machine-setup/<name>/description.
  WORKSPACE_INSTALLER        Installer the workspace fetches and runs (the workspace provisioner input).
  DOTFILES_INSTALLER         Installer the dotfiles fetch and run (the dotfiles provisioner input).
  XDG_STATE_HOME             Where the state store (managed markers, inputs) lives.
  <NAME>_<INPUT>             Pre-set a software input to keep the run unattended.
EOF
}
[[ -v TEST_FLAG ]] || readonly -f machine_setup::usage

#--------------------------------------------------
# Function:
#   machine_setup::install [name]...
#
# Description:
#   Runs the full set-up end to end. With no names it resolves the software
#   interactively (software::install::pick), installs it (software::install), then offers the
#   post-install provisioner toggle menu (provisioner::choose, both ticked) and runs
#   the ones left ticked (provisioner::provision_all). With one or more names it
#   installs exactly that software, unattended, and never touches the provisioners; a
#   provisioner name is not software and resolves to no software file, so it fails like
#   any other unknown name. Each selection is gathered before its phase acts.
#   Deselecting a piece never removes it: removal is a separate, explicit action
#   (uninstall). Carries every side effect of the set-up (the menus, prompting for
#   inputs, installing and configuring the software, then running the provisioners).
#   The worst status across the install and the provisioning is returned.
#
# Arguments:
#   [name]...  Zero or more software names; none triggers the interactive flow
#
# Returns:
#   0 when the set-up succeeded
#   N the worst status from the install and the provisioning
#
# Example:
#   machine_setup::install tree git
#--------------------------------------------------
machine_setup::install() {
    local -i failure
    local -a selected
    local selection
    local -i status

    # Own the run's session (warning and clearing a leftover one) before any menu,
    # so every subprocess inherits it and the lock is held for the whole run.
    session::begin || return $?

    if (($# > 0))
    then
        # A named, unattended run installs exactly the named software and never
        # touches the provisioners; a provisioner name is not software and resolves
        # to no software file, failing like any other unknown name.
        #
        # Capture the worst status through ||, never on a following line: the helper
        # returns the worst exit status it saw, and under set -e a bare call that
        # returns non-zero would abort here, skipping both the capture and the
        # session::end below. The || keeps set -e from firing and still records it.
        status=0
        software::install "$@" || status=$?
    else
        selection="$(software::install::pick)"
        selected=()
        [[ -z "$selection" ]] || mapfile -t selected <<<"$selection"

        # Capture through || so set -e does not abort on a non-zero worst status
        # before the provisioners and session::end below get to run.
        status=0
        software::install "${selected[@]}" || status=$?

        # The post-install step: offer the provisioner toggle menu (both ticked),
        # then run the ones left ticked, last, on top of the freshly installed tools.
        selection="$(provisioner::choose)"
        selected=()
        [[ -z "$selection" ]] || mapfile -t selected <<<"$selection"

        if ((${#selected[@]} > 0))
        then
            failure=0
            provisioner::provision_all "${selected[@]}" || failure=$?
            ((failure <= status)) || status=$failure
        fi
    fi

    # Close the session (clearing the working area) on the way out, whichever path
    # we leave by.
    session::end

    return "$status"
}
[[ -v TEST_FLAG ]] || readonly -f machine_setup::install

#--------------------------------------------------
# Function:
#   machine_setup::uninstall [name]...
#
# Description:
#   Removes software, the inverse of the set-up flow. With one or more names it
#   reverses exactly that software, unattended. With no names it opens the removal
#   menu (software::uninstall::pick over every removable piece - each unticked and
#   labelled with its current status) and reverses only the software the user ticks;
#   with no terminal the menu resolves to nothing, so an unattended run removes
#   nothing. The removal itself runs through software::uninstall (unconfigure then
#   uninstall per piece, worst-status semantics). The provisioners own no checkout, so
#   removal covers software only. Carries the side effects of the menu and of removing
#   the software.
#
# Arguments:
#   [name]...  Zero or more software names; none opens the interactive removal menu
#
# Returns:
#   0 when every piece was reversed or none were chosen
#   N propagated from software::uninstall
#
# Example:
#   machine_setup::uninstall git
#--------------------------------------------------
machine_setup::uninstall() {
    local removal
    local -a removals
    local -i status

    session::begin || return $?

    if (($# > 0))
    then
        removals=("$@")
    else
        removal="$(software::uninstall::pick)"
        removals=()
        [[ -z "$removal" ]] || mapfile -t removals <<<"$removal"
    fi

    # Capture through || so set -e does not abort on a non-zero worst status before
    # session::end runs.
    status=0
    software::uninstall "${removals[@]}" || status=$?

    session::end

    return "$status"
}
[[ -v TEST_FLAG ]] || readonly -f machine_setup::uninstall

# ─── Main ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

#--------------------------------------------------
# Function:
#   machine_setup::main [install [name...] | uninstall [name...] | status [name...]]
#
# Description:
#   Entry point. With -h, --help, or help it prints usage. The first argument is
#   an action: status reports the named software's status (or every piece when none
#   are named); uninstall reverses the named software (or opens the interactive
#   removal menu when none are named); install (the default when the first argument
#   is not a reserved action) runs the full set-up over the named software, or
#   interactively when none are named. Prints usage to stdout for help; the set-up,
#   removal, and status side effects are those of their handlers.
#
# Arguments:
#   install [name]...    Set up the named software (or interactively when none named)
#   uninstall [name]...  Remove the named software (or interactively when none named)
#   status [name]...     Report the named software's status (or every piece when none)
#
# Returns:
#   0 on success or after printing help
#   N propagated from the chosen handler
#
# Example:
#   machine_setup::main install tree
#--------------------------------------------------
machine_setup::main() {
    case "${1:-}" in
        -h | --help | help)
            machine_setup::usage

            return 0
            ;;
        status)
            shift
            software::status_report "$@"
            ;;
        install)
            shift
            machine_setup::install "$@"
            ;;
        uninstall)
            shift
            machine_setup::uninstall "$@"
            ;;
        *)
            # No reserved action: the arguments (if any) are software names to
            # set up, and no arguments means the interactive set-up.
            machine_setup::install "$@"
            ;;
    esac
}

# ─── Constants / globals ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# This script's directory and the repository root, resolved to absolute paths so
# the orchestrator sources its libraries regardless of the caller's working
# directory. Made readonly outside tests so specs can reassign.
ROOT="$(cd -- "$(dirname -- "${BASH_SOURCE[0]}")/.." && pwd)"
[[ -v TEST_FLAG ]] || readonly ROOT

# ─── Imports ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# shellcheck source=lib/provisioner.sh
source "$ROOT/lib/provisioner.sh"
# shellcheck source=lib/session.sh
source "$ROOT/lib/session.sh"
# shellcheck source=lib/software.sh
source "$ROOT/lib/software.sh"

# ─── Execute ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
[[ "${BASH_SOURCE[0]}" != "$0" ]] || machine_setup::main "$@"
